div.p:
Centuries before, the Psalmist gave us in outline, the horrors of body and mind of a
crucifixion and foretold the actual outcry of Christ on the cross, as in the very extreme of
mortal agony and of hopeless despair, he exclaimed: "My God, my God, why hast thou
forsaken me?" (Ps. 22:1;
Matt. 27:46;
Mark 15:34).

On that same day of the resurrection, the risen Christ appeared to Mary
(Mark 16:9;
John 20:11-18), to the women at the
tomb (Matt. 28:9-10),
to Peter (Luke 24:34;
1 Cor. 15:5), to the two
Disciples journeying to Emmaus (Luke 24:13-35),
and in that evening to all the Disciples except Thomas
(John 20:19-25);
a week later to all the Disciples including Thomas
(Mark 16:14-19;
John 20:26-29);
later still on the shores of the Sea of Tiberias, to Peter and those who had
also gone fishing (John 21:1-23);
and afterward to some five hundred of the brethren at once
(1 Cor. 15:6),
and to James (1 Cor. 15:7);
then to the living Disciples at a mountain in Galilee by appointment by the Christ
(Luke 24:36-52);
and lastly to the Disciples at the ascension
(Acts 1:1-9).
